body:
If you have successful usage of xml_rs in main.rs

```
// main.rs
extern crate xml;
use xml::reader::{EventReader, XmlEvent};
/* and here comes some XML-handling code */
```

And after working with it for a bit you move the XML code to xml_usecase.rs 

```
// main.rs
mod xml_usecase;
use xml_usecase::*;

// xml_usecase.rs
extern crate xml;
use xml::reader::{EventReader, XmlEvent};
/* and here comes some XML-handling code */
```

The same exact text will now spew error messages. The files by the way are in the same src directory.

Given the steep slopes a new rust developer must climb to code the little things, it seems like this is an unnecessary barrier to getting code from the point where it's all stuffed in a 1000-line main.rs to where the code is divided into logical pieces. 

[This S.O. answer](http://stackoverflow.com/a/27653246) says what to do about it. But one of the strategies means that code files can't be moved around without touching it inside the files. And the other one, putting the crate imports in the root, means that besides putting things in the cargo.toml and at the site of use, we are putting things in a file that should not know so much about so many things.

main.rs does need to "point to" xml_usecase.rs but it isn't very fluid to have to have xml_usecase.rs contain so much modification to its boiler-plate compared to how it looked when it cohabited with main.rs.
